Infrastructure Investment & Jobs Act Funding Allocation

Is the allocation equitable based on the population of each of the States and Territories, or is bias apparent?

Does the allocation favor the political interests of the Biden administration?

Notes:

You will need to source data on the current (estimated) population of each of the States and Territories (accuracy is more important than precision) and on the official election results of the 2020 Presidential election.

Preliminary Funding Review

state_funding_df <- readxl::read_excel(paste0(getwd(),'/',filename_funding))
state_funding_df <- state_funding_df |>
    rename("geographic_area"= "State, Teritory or Tribal Nation" ,'Dollars_Allocated'='Total (Billions)') |> mutate(geographic_area =gsub('DELEWARE','DELAWARE',geographic_area))

prez_voting_df <- prez_voting_df |> filter(year=='2020') |> mutate(percent_vote = candidatevotes/totalvotes) |> select(c(year,state,state_po,candidate,party_detailed,candidatevotes,totalvotes,percent_vote,party_simplified))

grouped_voting <- prez_voting_df |> group_by(state,party_simplified) |> summarise(sum_perc =sum(percent_vote)) |> summarise(top_party=max(sum_perc))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'state'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
top_party_df <- inner_join(prez_voting_df,grouped_voting,by=c("state"='state','percent_vote'='top_party'))
head(top_party_df)
## # A tibble: 6  9
##    year state      state_po candidate    party candi total perce party

fund_pop_df <- left_join(state_funding_df,american_pop_df,by=c("geographic_area"="geographic_area"))
dim(fund_pop_df)
## [1] 57  3
head(fund_pop_df)
## # A tibble: 6  3
##   geographic_area Dollars_Allocated population_2020
##   <chr>                       <dbl>           <dbl>
## 1 ALABAMA                    3              5024356
## 2 ALASKA                     3.7             733378
## 3 AMERICAN SAMOA             0.0686           49710
## 4 ARIZONA                    3.5            7151507
## 5 ARKANSAS                   2.8            3011555
## 6 CALIFORNIA                18.4           39538245
perc_totals <- fund_pop_df |>
summarise(perc_allocations=Dollars_Allocated/sum(Dollars_Allocated),perc_population=population_2020/sum(population_2020))

full_df <- cbind(fund_pop_df,perc_totals)
full_df <- full_df |> mutate(perc_diff=perc_allocations-perc_population,dollar_per_capita=10^9*Dollars_Allocated/population_2020)
full_votes_df <- left_join(full_df,top_party_df,by=c('geographic_area'='state'))

Visualizing IIJA Funding: Is there bias towards population or the presidents political party?

full_votes_df |> group_by(party_simplified) |> summarise(total_allocated=sum(Dollars_Allocated),percent_party_allocated=total_allocated/sum(full_votes_df$Dollars_Allocated)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=party_simplified,y=percent_party_allocated,fill=party_simplified)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
     scale_fill_manual(values=c('blue', 'red', 'grey')) +
    labs(x='Nominated 2020 Political Party',y='Percent of Total Dollars Allocated',title='Are total dollars allocated in the IIJA indicative of political bias?',subtitle='More exploration to follow as to why this chart does not tell the whole story',fill='Nominated 2020 Party')

full_votes_df$pop_scaled <- scale(full_votes_df$population_2020)
full_votes_df$dollars_scaled <- scale(full_votes_df$Dollars_Allocated)

ggplot(full_votes_df,aes(x=perc_population,y=perc_allocations)) +
    geom_point(aes(colour=party_simplified)) +
    geom_abline(slope=1, intercept = 0)+
    geom_text(aes(label=state_po),size=3.5,vjust=2) +
    labs(x='Percent of Total US Population',y='Percent of IIJA Funding Allocated',title='Assessing the relationship between US population and IIJA funding',subtitle='Larger populations do not always receive an equal allocation, but most are proportional',color='Nominated 2020 Party') +
    scale_color_manual(values=c('blue', 'red', 'grey')) +
    theme(legend.position = 'bottom')
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_text).

Zooming in on those states given funding above the line (per the prior chart)

ggplot(data=full_votes_df |> filter(perc_allocations>perc_population),aes(x=perc_population,y=perc_allocations)) +
    geom_point(aes(colour=party_simplified,size=4)) +
    geom_text(aes(label=state_po),size=3.5,vjust=2) +
    labs(x='Percent of Total US Population',y='Percent of IIJA Funding Allocated',title='States allocated IIJA funding more per capita',subtitle="More Republican states received additional IIJA funding when factoring population",color='Nominated 2020 Party') +
    scale_color_manual(values=c('blue', 'red', 'grey')) +
    guides(size="none")
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing missing values (geom_text).

All US states/territories per capita

ggplot(full_votes_df,aes(x=reorder(geographic_area,-dollar_per_capita),y=dollar_per_capita,fill=party_simplified)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    labs(title="Funding is not driven by population or current president's political party",
    x='US State/Territory',y='Dollars Per Capita',subtitle='More data and analysis is needed to identify bias with IIJA funding',fill='Nominated 2020 Party') +
    scale_fill_manual(values=c('blue', 'red', 'grey')) +
    theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 8,angle=90))

Subset of US States/Territories that received more funding than explained by their population

ggplot(full_votes_df|>filter(perc_allocations>perc_population)|>mutate(Population_Rank=rank(-population_2020)),aes(x=reorder(geographic_area,-dollar_per_capita),y=dollar_per_capita,fill=party_simplified)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    labs(title="Data does not indicate clear bias for higher per capita locations",
    x='US State/Territory',y='Dollars Per Capita',subtitle='Perhaps political compromise was needed to finalize the deal',fill='Nominated 2020 Party') +
    scale_fill_manual(values=c('blue', 'red', 'grey')) +
    theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 8,angle=90))
